---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Organizing CSV & Tabular Data — Using AI Agents for Real Tasks"
  description="Have AI help you read tables, organize them, check them, and produce summaries you can keep using. Starting from an event sign-up CSV, you'll practice using Gemini CLI to read local files, run basic statistics, surface data issues, and finally draft a reminder."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container ai-agent-csv">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Putting AI Agents to Work on a First Real Task: Tabular Data</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          AI workflows aren't about letting the model run wild. They're about <strong>breaking the task into clear steps</strong> and letting AI help inside a safe, checkable boundary. This page applies AI agents to a very common task: <strong>organizing CSV and tabular data</strong>.
        </p>
      </header>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Whether it's an event sign-up sheet, survey results, a course roster, a reading list, or interview notes — most data ends up in a table. <strong>It looks simple, but cleaning it up usually surfaces several problems</strong>:
      </p>

      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li><strong>Inconsistent formatting</strong> across rows</li>
        <li>Some columns are <strong>blank</strong></li>
        <li>The same meaning is written in <strong>different ways</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Column names are unclear</strong></li>
        <li>You want to summarize but <strong>don't know where to start</strong></li>
        <li>You want a digest, but worry the <strong>AI will just make things up</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So what we're practicing here isn't deep data analysis. It's:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Letting AI <strong>read, organize, and check tables</strong>,<br/>
          and produce <strong>summaries you can keep using</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Section: build practice data ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Build a CSV practice file first</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        We'll prepare an "<strong>event sign-up</strong>" sheet. In VS Code, create a project folder called <code>csv-agent-practice</code>, then a <code>data</code> folder inside it, and place <code>activity_signup.csv</code> there. The folder structure looks like:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>csv-agent-practice
└─ data
   └─ activity_signup.csv</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        File contents (save as <strong>CSV UTF-8</strong>):
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>name,department,session,diet,needs_certificate,notes
Wang Xiaoming,Chinese Y2,Morning,Meat,Yes,
Li Jiaying,History Y3,Afternoon,Vegetarian,No,Wants front row
Chen Boyu,Sociology Y1,Morning,,Yes,Diet not filled
Lin Yijun,Foreign Lang Y4,Afternoon,Meat,Yes,
Zhang Tingxuan,Psychology Y2,Morning,Vegetarian,Yes,Will be 10 min late
Huang Zihao,Communication Y3,Afternoon,Meat,No,
Wu Yating,Education Y1,Morning,Vegetarian,Yes,
Zheng Yuxiang,Law Y2,Afternoon,,No,Diet not filled</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Viewed as a table, it looks like:
      </p>

      <div class="csv-table-wrapper">
        <table class="csv-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Name</th>
              <th>Department</th>
              <th>Session</th>
              <th>Diet</th>
              <th>Needs Cert.</th>
              <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Wang Xiaoming</td><td>Chinese Y2</td><td>Morning</td><td>Meat</td><td>Yes</td><td></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Li Jiaying</td><td>History Y3</td><td>Afternoon</td><td>Vegetarian</td><td>No</td><td>Wants front row</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chen Boyu</td><td>Sociology Y1</td><td>Morning</td><td class="csv-empty">—</td><td>Yes</td><td>Diet not filled</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Lin Yijun</td><td>Foreign Lang Y4</td><td>Afternoon</td><td>Meat</td><td>Yes</td><td></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Zhang Tingxuan</td><td>Psychology Y2</td><td>Morning</td><td>Vegetarian</td><td>Yes</td><td>Will be 10 min late</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Huang Zihao</td><td>Communication Y3</td><td>Afternoon</td><td>Meat</td><td>No</td><td></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Wu Yating</td><td>Education Y1</td><td>Morning</td><td>Vegetarian</td><td>Yes</td><td></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Zheng Yuxiang</td><td>Law Y2</td><td>Afternoon</td><td class="csv-empty">—</td><td>No</td><td>Diet not filled</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        It's a small dataset, but a good practice fit because it contains several common situations:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Some people <strong>didn't fill in their diet</strong></li>
        <li>The notes column is <strong>partly empty</strong>, partly contains <strong>extra requests</strong></li>
        <li>You may want to know <strong>how many people are in each session</strong></li>
        <li>You may want to list <strong>who needs an attendance certificate</strong></li>
        <li>You may want AI to help <strong>check whether the data is complete</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <!-- ============ Section: read CSV file ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Let Gemini CLI read a local file</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The exercise is <strong>not</strong> to paste CSV content into the prompt — it's to let Gemini CLI read a local file. Gemini CLI can use <code>@file_path</code> to add a file or folder's contents to the prompt; given a single file path, it reads that file.
      </p>

      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li>
          <span class="numbered-list__num">1</span>
          <span class="numbered-list__text">Open the folder you just created — <code>csv-agent-practice</code> — in <strong>VS Code</strong>.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="numbered-list__num">2</span>
          <span class="numbered-list__text">Open a terminal (<strong>Terminal → New Terminal</strong>) and confirm the working directory is <code>csv-agent-practice</code>.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="numbered-list__num">3</span>
          <span class="numbered-list__text">Run <code>uv init</code> to <strong>initialize the project</strong>.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="numbered-list__num">4</span>
          <span class="numbered-list__text">Run <code>gemini</code> to <strong>start Gemini CLI</strong>.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="numbered-list__num">5</span>
          <span class="numbered-list__text">Each exercise below uses this file path: <code>@./data/activity_signup.csv</code>.</span>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          <code>@./data/activity_signup.csv</code> means: please ask Gemini CLI to read <code>activity_signup.csv</code> in the <code>data</code> folder under the current project directory.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Part: practice ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PRACTICE</span>
        <span class="part-text">Prompt Exercises</span>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Run the four exercises below in order. <strong>At each step, confirm the AI got it right</strong> before moving on. If something looks off, stop and fix it — don't rush ahead.
      </p>

      <!-- Exercise 1 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">EXERCISE 1</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">First, make sure the AI understands the data</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The goal is to confirm whether the AI has actually understood the data. <strong>Don't rush into counting people or producing announcements yet.</strong> Confirm three things first:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Did the AI <strong>read the right file</strong>?</li>
        <li>Does it <strong>understand the column names</strong>?</li>
        <li>Does it know <strong>what questions this dataset can answer</strong>?</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If the AI misreads a column up front, every later step inherits that mistake.
      </p>

      <p class="prompt-label">Prompt example</p>
      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please read @./data/activity_signup.csv.<br/><br/>
        Don't analyze counts yet, and don't produce any announcement.<br/><br/>
        Please summarize:<br/>
        1. What columns does this file contain?<br/>
        2. What does each column mean?<br/>
        3. What kinds of questions is this data suitable for answering?<br/>
        4. Where might human verification be needed?<br/><br/>
        Answer based only on the file contents — don't invent data that isn't there.
      </blockquote>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Possible response</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand a sample response</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <h4 class="example-heading">1. What columns does this file contain?</h4>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">The file contains 6 columns: name, department, session, diet, needs_certificate, notes.</p>

          <h4 class="example-heading">2. What does each column mean?</h4>
          <ul class="role-list role-list--compact">
            <li class="role-item">
              <span class="role-item__label">name</span>
              <span class="role-item__desc">The participant's name</span>
            </li>
            <li class="role-item">
              <span class="role-item__label">department</span>
              <span class="role-item__desc">Department and year (e.g. Chinese Y2, History Y3)</span>
            </li>
            <li class="role-item">
              <span class="role-item__label">session</span>
              <span class="role-item__desc">Time slot they registered for (Morning or Afternoon)</span>
            </li>
            <li class="role-item">
              <span class="role-item__label">diet</span>
              <span class="role-item__desc">Dietary preference (Meat, Vegetarian, or blank)</span>
            </li>
            <li class="role-item">
              <span class="role-item__label">needs_certificate</span>
              <span class="role-item__desc">Whether they need an attendance certificate (Yes / No)</span>
            </li>
            <li class="role-item">
              <span class="role-item__label">notes</span>
              <span class="role-item__desc">Extra requests or context (e.g. wants front row, will be late, diet not filled)</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h4 class="example-heading">3. What questions can this data answer?</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Who registered for the morning session, and who for the afternoon?</li>
            <li>What department / year does a given participant belong to?</li>
            <li>Who has a clearly filled-in dietary preference?</li>
            <li>Who has additional requests in the notes column?</li>
            <li>Who needs an attendance certificate?</li>
          </ul>

          <h4 class="example-heading">4. Where might human verification be needed?</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Chen Boyu and Zheng Yuxiang's <strong>diet column is blank</strong>; the notes column says "Diet not filled," but their actual preference still needs to be confirmed</li>
            <li>Li Jiaying wants to <strong>sit in the front row</strong> — confirm whether the venue can accommodate this</li>
            <li>Zhang Tingxuan said she <strong>will be 10 minutes late</strong> — confirm whether this affects check-in</li>
            <li>The department format ("Department + Year") could be checked for consistency across rows</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The point of this response isn't depth of analysis — it's <strong>confirming whether the AI has actually understood the data structure</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Exercise 2 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">EXERCISE 2</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Run basic statistics</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The goal is to have the AI run <strong>simple categorical counts</strong> on the CSV — how many people per session, how many vegetarians, who needs a certificate. This step turns one flat table into <strong>something easier to read at a glance</strong>.
      </p>

      <p class="prompt-label">Prompt example</p>
      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please read @./data/activity_signup.csv and produce basic statistics from the file contents.<br/><br/>
        Please answer:<br/>
        1. How many people in the morning session? List names.<br/>
        2. How many in the afternoon session? List names.<br/>
        3. How many meat-eaters? List names.<br/>
        4. How many vegetarians? List names.<br/>
        5. How many people have a blank or missing diet? List names.<br/>
        6. How many people need a certificate? List names.<br/><br/>
        Please present the results in a table.<br/>
        Use only the contents of the file — don't add anything or guess.
      </blockquote>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Possible response</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand a sample response</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">Basic statistics from the file:</p>

          <div class="csv-table-wrapper">
            <table class="csv-table csv-table--stat">
              <thead>
                <tr><th>Item</th><th>Count</th><th>Names</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>Morning session</td><td class="csv-num">4</td><td>Wang Xiaoming, Chen Boyu, Zhang Tingxuan, Wu Yating</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Afternoon session</td><td class="csv-num">4</td><td>Li Jiaying, Lin Yijun, Huang Zihao, Zheng Yuxiang</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Meat</td><td class="csv-num">3</td><td>Wang Xiaoming, Lin Yijun, Huang Zihao</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Vegetarian</td><td class="csv-num">3</td><td>Li Jiaying, Zhang Tingxuan, Wu Yating</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Diet not filled</td><td class="csv-num">2</td><td>Chen Boyu, Zheng Yuxiang</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Needs certificate</td><td class="csv-num">5</td><td>Wang Xiaoming, Chen Boyu, Lin Yijun, Zhang Tingxuan, Wu Yating</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Notes on the statistics</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li><strong>Session split</strong>: Morning and afternoon each have 4 people</li>
            <li><strong>Diet</strong>: 3 meat-eaters, 3 vegetarians, 2 blanks</li>
            <li><strong>Certificate</strong>: 5 people marked "Yes" under needs_certificate</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <div class="callout-card callout-card--warn">
        <p class="callout-text">
          <strong>AI is good at organizing, but a human still needs to check.</strong> The risk of miscounting grows with row count, so before any official use, verify with a spreadsheet or script as well.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Exercise 3 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">EXERCISE 3</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Surface the data issues that need handling</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The goal is to have the AI help <strong>check whether the data is complete</strong>. Cleaning up a table is rarely just about counting — it's also about finding:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Where it's <strong>blank</strong></li>
        <li>What needs to be <strong>verified</strong></li>
        <li>Which fields will <strong>affect later arrangements</strong></li>
        <li>Which gaps the <strong>AI must not fill in by itself</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The point isn't to ask the AI to modify data — it's to <strong>have the AI flag issues so a human can verify them</strong>.
      </p>

      <p class="prompt-label">Prompt example</p>
      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please read @./data/activity_signup.csv and check this dataset for anything that needs human verification.<br/><br/>
        Please specifically check:<br/>
        1. Which columns are blank?<br/>
        2. Which entries could affect later arrangements?<br/>
        3. Whose data needs to be re-confirmed?<br/>
        4. Which gaps must NOT be filled in by AI?<br/><br/>
        Please answer in this format:<br/><br/>
        　Data issues:<br/>
        　People to verify:<br/>
        　Possible impact:<br/>
        　Recommended next step:<br/><br/>
        Don't modify the original file, and don't fill in answers for blank fields.
      </blockquote>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Possible response</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand a sample response</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <h4 class="example-heading">Data issues</h4>
          <ol class="numbered-list">
            <li>
              <span class="numbered-list__num">1</span>
              <span class="numbered-list__text"><strong>Blank columns</strong>: diet — Chen Boyu, Zheng Yuxiang; notes — Wang Xiaoming, Lin Yijun, Huang Zihao, Wu Yating.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="numbered-list__num">2</span>
              <span class="numbered-list__text"><strong>Special notes</strong>: Li Jiaying wants the front row; Zhang Tingxuan will be 10 minutes late.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="numbered-list__num">3</span>
              <span class="numbered-list__text"><strong>Gaps the AI shouldn't fill</strong>: diet is a personal health or belief preference — guessing wrong could create safety problems. Notes about seating or timing involve personal preferences and must be filled based on actual communication.</span>
            </li>
          </ol>

          <h4 class="example-heading">People to verify</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li><strong>Chen Boyu, Zheng Yuxiang</strong>: confirm their actual diet</li>
            <li><strong>Li Jiaying</strong>: confirm whether the venue can accommodate her seating request</li>
            <li><strong>Zhang Tingxuan</strong>: confirm whether being 10 minutes late means missing key items (e.g. check-in materials)</li>
          </ul>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Possible impact</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li><strong>Catering</strong>: missing diet info could lead to wrong meal counts or types on the day</li>
            <li><strong>Venue setup</strong>: an unconfirmed seating request can create on-site adjustment problems</li>
            <li><strong>Check-in flow</strong>: a late arrival may slow the start or require extra staff to direct her</li>
          </ul>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Recommended next step</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li><strong>Reach out</strong> to Chen Boyu and Zheng Yuxiang to confirm diet, then update the data</li>
            <li>Reply to Li Jiaying about her seat, and mark "arranged" or "depends on venue" in the list</li>
            <li>Notify check-in staff that Zhang Tingxuan will be late, and reserve her materials</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          The AI should <strong>not fill in blanks on its own</strong>.<br/>
          It should <strong>flag the issues and remind the user to verify</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This mirrors a workflow principle from earlier: <strong>when data is missing, stop. Don't guess</strong>.
      </p>

      <!-- Exercise 4 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">EXERCISE 4</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Turn the data into a draft event reminder</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The previous three exercises walked through "<strong>understand → count → flag</strong>." Now we can have the AI draft an event reminder from the data — but <strong>still not publish anything directly</strong>. The safer pattern is:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Have the AI produce a <strong>draft</strong></li>
        <li>Have the AI list a <strong>data summary</strong></li>
        <li>Have the AI surface <strong>what still needs human verification</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Whether to publish remains a human decision.
      </p>

      <p class="prompt-label">Prompt example</p>
      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please read @./data/activity_signup.csv and produce a pre-event reminder draft based on the file contents.<br/><br/>
        Please follow these rules:<br/>
        1. Use only data that appears in the CSV.<br/>
        2. Don't publicly list every participant's name.<br/>
        3. Remind participants to attend the session they registered for.<br/>
        4. Remind people whose diet is blank to fill it in soon.<br/>
        5. Remind people who need a certificate to follow the organizer's instructions afterward.<br/>
        6. This is a draft only — don't publish it on my behalf.<br/>
        7. At the end, list what still needs human verification.<br/><br/>
        Please answer in this format:<br/><br/>
        　Reminder draft:<br/>
        　Data summary:<br/>
        　Items needing human verification:
      </blockquote>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Possible response</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand a sample response</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <h4 class="example-heading">Reminder draft</h4>
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            [Pre-event Notice & Reminder]<br/><br/>
            Hello everyone — the event is approaching. Please note the following:<br/><br/>
            1. <strong>Session confirmation</strong>: please attend the session you registered for (morning or afternoon).<br/>
            2. <strong>Diet info</strong>: a few participants haven't filled in the diet field yet. To ensure correct catering, please contact the organizer to update it.<br/>
            3. <strong>Certificate pickup</strong>: those who selected "Needs certificate" can pick it up after the event according to on-site staff guidance.<br/>
            4. <strong>Special notes</strong>: if you submitted a special request (seating, timing) at registration, the organizer has it on record. Please follow on-site arrangements on the day.
          </blockquote>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Data summary</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Total registrations: <strong>8</strong></li>
            <li>Session split: 4 morning, 4 afternoon</li>
            <li>Certificate: <strong>5</strong> need an attendance certificate</li>
            <li>Diet: 3 meat, 3 vegetarian, 2 blank</li>
            <li>Special requests: 1 seating request, 1 expected late arrival</li>
          </ul>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Items needing human verification</h4>
          <ol class="numbered-list">
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><strong>Diet follow-up</strong>: contact "Chen B." and "Zheng Y." to confirm their preferences.</span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><strong>Seating reply</strong>: confirm front-row arrangement for "Li J." and tag the seating chart.</span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><strong>Check-in prep</strong>: notify check-in staff that "Zhang T." will be 10 minutes late so her materials are reserved.</span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><strong>Certificate prep</strong>: cross-check the 5 people needing certificates and prepare the documents in advance.</span></li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </details>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          This exercise has stepped into <strong>"draft-style workflows."</strong> The AI is no longer just counting — it's <strong>turning organized table data into usable text</strong>. The final review still belongs to a human.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Section: troubleshoot ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">If Gemini CLI can't find the file</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Sometimes Gemini CLI will report that it <strong>can't find the file</strong>. In that case, check a few things:
      </p>

      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li>
          <span class="numbered-list__num">1</span>
          <span class="numbered-list__text">Confirm the file <strong>actually exists</strong>: <code>csv-agent-practice/data/activity_signup.csv</code>.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="numbered-list__num">2</span>
          <span class="numbered-list__text">Confirm you <strong>started Gemini CLI from inside</strong> <code>csv-agent-practice</code>.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="numbered-list__num">3</span>
          <span class="numbered-list__text">Confirm the path in your prompt is <code>@./data/activity_signup.csv</code>.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="numbered-list__num">4</span>
          <span class="numbered-list__text">If the folder or filename <strong>contains spaces</strong>, avoid them, or escape the path according to the tool's rules.</span>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          When starting out, stick to <strong>letters, numbers, underscores, or hyphens</strong> for folder and file names — e.g. <code>data</code>, <code>activity_signup.csv</code>, <code>course_feedback.csv</code>, <code>reading_list.csv</code>. Fewer surprises that way.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Section: takeaway ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">The most important idea on this page</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Organizing CSV and tabular data is <strong>not "hand the data to AI and let it freestyle."</strong> A more reliable approach is:
      </p>

      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text">First, have the AI <strong>read the file</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Then, have it <strong>understand the columns</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Next, run <strong>basic statistics</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Then, <strong>flag the data issues</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">5</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Only at the end, produce a <strong>summary or draft</strong></span></li>
      </ol>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The benefit: <strong>every step is checkable</strong>. If column understanding is wrong at step 1, you stop right there. If counting goes sideways, you can roll back. When data is missing, don't let the AI guess.
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>The table is the <strong>source of truth</strong></li>
        <li>The AI is an <strong>organizing assistant</strong></li>
        <li>Don't <strong>casually modify the original data</strong></li>
        <li>The final call still belongs to <strong>a human</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="highlight-card highlight-card--final">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          AI is good at helping organize tabular data,<br/>
          but its job is to <strong>assist</strong>, not to <strong>replace</strong>.<br/>
          The final decision still rests with <strong>a person</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

